					In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, New York City was hit by a series of heat waves that proved especially catastrophic for poor tenement dwellers. The most severe occurred in 1896 and claimed 1,300 lives. Here, young New Yorkers cool off in a fountain. (Photo Credit: Library of Congress)
